  "prompt": "How is the collation used for SQL Server determined?",
  "response": "In SQL Server, collation determines how data is sorted and compared. Here are the key points about collation determination:\n\n1. Default Collation Levels:\n- Server-level collation\n- Database-level collation\n- Column-level collation\n- Query-level collation\n\n2. Collation Determination Hierarchy:\n- Server default collation is set during SQL Server installation\n- Database inherits server collation if not specified during creation\n- Columns can have specific collations\n- Queries can use COLLATE clause to override existing collations\n\n3. Factors Influencing Collation:\n- Language settings\n- Character set\n- Case sensitivity\n- Accent sensitivity\n- Kana sensitivity\n- Width sensitivity\n\n4. Common Collation Naming Convention:\n[Language]_[Country/Region]_[Case Sensitivity]\nExamples:\n- SQL_Latin1_General_CP1_CI_AS\n- Latin1_General_BIN\n- Latin1_General_CI_AI\n\n5. Changing Collation:\n- Can be modified at server, database, or column level\n- Requires careful planning to avoid data conversion issues\n\n6. Determining Current Collation:\n- Server: SELECT SERVERPROPERTY('Collation')\n- Database: SELECT DATABASEPROPERTYEX(DB_NAME(), 'Collation')\n\nUnderstanding collation helps manage data sorting and comparison effectively.",
